snippet.textDisplay:
The reason that Rotten Tomatoes Audience Score is so vastly different is because in May of 2019, Rotten Tomatoes changed the way it calculates this score. After May, Rotten Tomatoes now scores the "Audience Score" based almost entirely on Fandango ticket purchases. If you didn't buy your ticket from Fandango, your score won't be tabulated into "Audience Score", with the exception that a staffer at Rotten Tomatoes hand picks your non-contributing review for inclusion... which now allows Rotten Tomatoes to actually game the Audience Score.

Audience Score doesn't constitute a "vocal minority", but it does constitute a "manipulated minority". What this means is that all the studios have to do is "persuade" their staff to use Fandango to buy tickets to a showing and then these staffers can rate the film higher than the "normal audience" who chooses to buy their tickets by other means, such as at the box office. It definitely means that regular moviegoers who choose to buy their tickets at the box office or by means other than Fandango won't have their rating tabulated into Rotten Tomatoes Audience Score. It's actually a very sleazy tactic in play by Rotten Tomatoes. It's also a tactic that can be easily gamed by anyone who understands how it works, including Rotten Tomatoes themselves.

snippet.textDisplay: The original trilogy is inspired by the 'hero archetype' and the work of Joseph Campbell (Campbell was even invited to Skywalker ranch by Lucas to watch the films, in which Lucas said he was inspired by them). What you have is the hero archetype in Luke--a representation of the aspirations and positive/striving against all odds energies in all of us (also the father/son relationship but not important right now). The opportunity missed in these films is truly tragic. We have an opportunity not often explored in film--what happens when the hero ends his quest? What does the second half of his life look like? How does he grow in wisdom? The last Jedi says that he does not grow, but regresses into skepticism, resentment and anger. Thus the death of our archetype ( yet admittedly a reflection of a good group of people in America as  anyone can attest to the 'get off my lawn' person). Luke's character assassination was a tragedy put at the foot of Ryan Johnson who simply leveraged his character as an lazy way of creating shock and drama. I sincerely doubt that he even knows about Campbell's work...about mythology and its function, and about the archetypes involved that live in the minds of all fans of the franchise.
